Reposting some ideas for the dwarf sheep from last thread.
Any anons got some input/thoughts I'd love to hear them.

While I am waiting for version 2 of the reference sheet for the dweep (the dwarf sheep) who is still unnamed, I thought I would share some ideas I had about their species.

>are actual dwarves
>pissed off some ancient god or something and got turned into a beast race of dwarves
>roll with it and move south
>speak in both refined and more "hillbilly" Southern accents and colloquialisms
>Males and females are usually easy going and slow to anger.
>Not afraid of fighting
>past times include feasts/festivals, drinking and fighting
>Prefer plains and grasslands to mountains
>strong agricultural lifestyle, farms and the life
>smiths make masterwork farm tools, hoes, axes etc. They are also no stranger to tools of war
>runic markings that have mystical properties
>gilding of horns is done for holy days or occasions, or as a symbol of status
>long lived species. Reach adulthood around 90 years of age and usually live past 300
>are infatuated with humans finding their short and very busy lives fascinating.

That's what I've got so far. I'm still thinking out how their social structure is based, who owns land, or does what. I'm thinking they're a bit feudal in that regard.

Man I've given suggestions on damn near every single time you posted Anon. Here's hoping this time also doesn't disappoint.

>Collectivists, but very oriented towards a family core, introducing new members to most of their relatives and family whenever they're born or whenever a sufficient bond is established, be it economic or social
>In matters of marriage and union, especially with members of an opposite race or land, this fact is exacerbated even more, with the human tradition of meeting the father, mother and siblings extended to aunts, uncles and more, given a judicious, if perhaps more lenient inspection than on a human family
>Being so united in both clan, family and land, sharing something with those they consider to be allies, acquaintances or enemies has a much deeper meaning than what might in other lands.
>This usually implies something like sharing a drink with the same chalice for a friend, a respectful, perhaps begrudging bottle between enemy generals after a clash, or of course, the sharing of a bed between lovers and those already engaged.
>Of course, if the union is particularly strong, or if they intend to make it strong to forge an alliance of trade or the union of clans and families, this can be extended further.
>The sharing of sigils. The carving of ones skin with inks and perhaps blades. To share ones message across two bodies carries extra meaning, and while in human lands a tatoo of your loved ones name may be tacky, in Dwarven society, it is seen as the greatest honor you can give to whoever you care for, romantically or simply in a platonic way of respect

>Land ownership is usually clan/guild based but subpartitions are done according to internal ranks of the guilds, with the position of "King" being dependant on the status of the guild or clan and how they are perceived.
1/2

Anonymous Mon 22 Nov 2021 00:43:55 No.43370737 Report

>>43370502
>Care to expand on this a bit anon? I think I know what you mean but I'd like to hear some more thoughts.
Basically, every setting has a max power and a min power for an average person, and a certain different range for heroics or protagonists. When you introduce magic, often you restrict the highest power to literal decades of either intense training, absolute monastic tradition, academic study, dangerous demonic bargains or whatever else, but magic alone if its left available to individuals on something like a artificer like level permits shit to change a lot and for stuff like offensive magic weapons for a slightly richer man.

What this means for Sci fi is that you have to be very careful to make sure that, unless you are a hero and with the connections and power and cash of a hero, you aren't packing some kind of laser mini gun, archeotech shield gen and body mods that make you Samurai Jack. You limit it to something like a weak personal shield with maybe 3 shots worth of battery, a laser taser hybrid gun and something like a head aiming assistance guidance module with a scouter for a civilian really into the whole shebang, and you don't give the military something like a portable black hole maker. You establish your power level, both the highest and the lowest within your story context and social-economical area and make sure to not surpass it so the story doesn't become absurd, because when the Dweep is bleeding out on the floor and the Protag is stressed about it, they shouldn't have something civilian available like a hyper stimulant syringe to keep em alive because civvies don't get that. If everything is solved by tech, there's no drama and there's no suspense because tech is everywhere, on everyone and solves everything.
